  "dateModified": "2026-03-03",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-03",
  "description": "The rhetorical sequence that fascist political speech follows regardless of its surface content: declare crisis, name a pure community, denounce enemies as sterile or corrupt, reframe suffering as sacrifice, promise destiny, assert inevitability. The concept distinguishes grammar from ideology — an ideology is a set of beliefs, but a grammar is a structure that generates statements regardless of their specific content. Fascist grammar can generate fascist politics, but it can also generate postliberal Catholic integralism, left-wing populism, or liberal crisis rhetoric. The grammar is the deep structure; the politics is the surface. Liberalism does not escape fascist grammar by opposing it — it inhabits the grammar in reverse, preserving the structure step-for-step while negating each move. Anarchist grammar names a different sequence entirely (condition, commons, relation, solidarity, desire, immanence) that does not preserve the same structure.",
  "name": "Fascist grammar",
